							<div class="rowTxt">
							
							
							
								<p class="newsHead">Major changes proposed to Scottish Civil Justice System</p>
								<p class="newsDate">Jan&nbsp;2010</p>
								<p><p>Lord Gill, a senior Court of Session judge, was tasked by the Scottish Government in 2007 to carry out a wholesale review of our systems and procedures and over the successive 2 years, Lord Gill consulted extensively with a view to making recommendations which would bring about improving access to justice in Scotland, promote the early resolution of disputes, make the best use of resources and ensure cases are dealt with in ways which are proportionate to their value and complexity. It is fair to say the compilers of the Report were of the view that reform is long overdue.</p><p>Early signs are that there is the political and judicial will to implement Lord Gill’s reforms. A number of the reforms will require legislation and due to the Scottish election next year, it is likely it will be 2012 before we see any Bills. <br />In brief, the headline recommendations are as follows:</p><p>1. Scotland should have an additional Court tier by creating the role of District Judge who will be able to hear minor criminal cases, civil claims where the sum in dispute is less than £5000 and some family cases. This brings the Scottish system in line with England and many other countries and will substantially free up existing judges to hear more complex cases which should result in cases being dealt with more efficiently.</p><p>2. A new case management model will be introduced for all civil cases which will essentially mean that cases will be allocated to a particular judge who will then see the case through to conclusion, that Court procedure will take place through email and conference calls (thus avoiding the need for parties to attend Court for no evidential hearings) with judges having the ability to call for early exchange of information with a view to facilitating settlement and ease of preparation. </p><p>3. There will be a significant increase to the privative jurisdiction of Sheriff Courts (where most business is carried out) thus freeing up the Court of Session (Scotland’s supreme civil court) to hear the most complex and high value cases.</p><p>It is beyond question that the reforms will bring about significant improvement to the operation of the civil justice system in Scotland.</p><p>One area the Report did not manage to look at in any detail relates to the costs of litigation and how the same is funded. The authors felt this was a huge topic in its own right and recommend this is looked at separately. The Report suggests establishing an independent body, to be called the Civil Justice Council for Scotland, to draft necessary Court rules and to keep civil justice under review and develop proposals for change. It would be expected that such a Council would look at funding issues as a priority following inceptions.</p><p>The next few years will be exciting for all those working in the civil justice system in Scotland. We will aim to keep all our clients up to date as reforms are implemented. This update is intended to give readers a ‘heads up’ as to what may lie ahead.</p></p>
								
								
								<img src="../../content/cms/uploads/large/21523.jpg"  />
								
